Adjust rack to top position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry all
produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Heat
a drizzle of @oil{} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites;
cook ~{1%minute}. Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup} and @water{3/4%cup}. Bring to a
boil, then cover and reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.
Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, drain @mango{4%oz}, discarding juice; roughly chop. Trim
@green beans{6%oz}, if necessary. Zest and quarter @lime{1} (for 4 servings, zest
1 lime and quarter both). In a #small bowl{}, combine mango, scallion greens,
and a squeeze of lime juice to taste. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Toss green beans on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of oil, salt, and pepper.
Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

While green beans roast, pat @Australis barramundi{10%oz} dry with paper towels;
season all over with salt and pepper. Season flesh sides with @Southwest spice
blend{1%tbsp}; rub to evenly coat.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{4%tsp} in a #large pan{} over medium-high
heat. Add barramundi skin sides down. Cook until skin is crispy, ~{4-5%minutes}.
(TIP: Lower heat if skin begins to brown too quickly.) Flip and cook until fish
is opaque and cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes}. Remove pan from heat.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} and lime zest. Season with
salt and pepper. Divide rice, barramundi, and green beans between plates. Top
fish with salsa. Serve with remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Mango salsa is our favorite way to feel warm weather vibes all year round. It's
> sweet, juicy, and tangy, making it the perfect complement to crispy, spiced
> barramundi. No matter the temperature, one bite of this delicious dish will
> make everything feel a whole lot sunnier.